Expansion of eta(q^2)^7 * eta(q^8)^2 / (eta(q)^2 * eta(q^4)^7) in powers of q.

Expansion of phi(x) / phi(x^2) where phi() is a Ramanujan theta function.
G.f. A(x) satisfies 0 = f(A(x), A(x^2)) where f(u, v) = 1 + (1 - u*v)^2 - v^2. - _Michael Somos_, Jan 31 2006

A080030.name: a(n) is taken to be the smallest positive integer not already present which is consistent with the condition "n is a member of the sequence if and only if a(n) is congruent to 1 mod 3".

A080033.name: a(n) is taken to be the smallest positive integer not already present which is consistent with the condition "n is a member of the sequence if and only if a(n) is a multiple of 4".

A080037.name: a(0)=2; for n > 0, a(n) = n + floor(sqrt(4n-3)) + 2.

A080039.name: a(n) = floor((1+sqrt(2))^n).
formula: Comments from _Hieronymus Fischer_, Jan 02 2009 (Start): The fractional part of (1+sqrt(2))^n equals (1+sqrt(2))^(-n), if n odd. For even n, the fractional part of (1+sqrt(2))^n is equal to 1-(1+sqrt(2))^(-n).
See A001622 for a general formula concerning the fractional parts of powers of numbers x>1, which satisfy x-x^(-1)=floor(x).

A080040.name: a(n) = 2*a(n-1) + 2*a(n-2) for n > 1; a(0)=2, a(1)=2.
formula: G.f.: G(0), where G(k) = 1 + 1/(1 - x*(3*k-1)/(x*(3*k+2) - 1/G(k+1))); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Jun 11 2013
a(n) = [x^n] ( 1 + x + sqrt(1 + 2*x + 3*x^2) )^n for n >= 1. - _Peter Bala_, Jun 29 2015

A080042.name: a(n) = 4*a(n-1)+3*a(n-2) for n>1, a(0)=2, a(1)=4.
formula: G.f.: G(0)/x -2/x, where G(k)= 1 + 1/(1 - x*(7*k-4)/(x*(7*k+3) - 2/G(k+1))); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Jun 03 2013

A080044.name: Numerators of triangular array: T(n,1)=T(n,n)=1/n and T(n,k)=T(n-1,k-1)+T(n-1,k), 1<k<n.

A080045.name: Denominators of triangular array: T(n,1)=T(n,n)=1/n and T(n,k)=T(n-1,k-1)+t(n-1,k), 1<k<n.

A080047.name: Operation count to create all permutations of n distinct elements using Algorithm L (lexicographic permutation generation) from Knuth's The Art of Computer Programming, Vol. 4, chapter 7.2.1.2. Sequence gives number of times l has to be repeatedly decreased in step L3.

A080048.name: Operation count to create all permutations of n distinct elements using Algorithm L (lexicographic permutation generation) from Knuth's The Art of Computer Programming, Vol. 4, chapter 7.2.1.2. Sequence gives number of loop repetitions in reversal step.

A080049.name: Operation count to create all permutations of n distinct elements using Algorithm L (lexicographic permutation generation) from Knuth's The Art of Computer Programming, Vol. 4, chapter 7.2.1.2. Sequence gives number of interchange operations in step L4.

A080051.name: Common factors of 2^p-1 and the p-th Fibonacci number, p prime.

A080052.name: Value of n such that for any value of n, Pi^n is closer to its nearest integer than any value of Pi^k for 1 <= k < n.

A080054.name: G.f.: Product_{n >= 0} (1+x^(2n+1))/(1-x^(2n+1)).
formula: Expansion of f(q) / f(-q) in powers of q where f() is a Ramanujan theta function.
Expansion of (1 - k^2)^(-1/8) = k'^(-1/4) in powers of the nome q = exp(-Pi K'/K).
Expansion of eta(q^2)^3 / (eta(q^4) * eta(q)^2) in powers of q.
(theta_3(q) / theta_4(q))^(1/2) = (phi(q) / phi(-q))^(1/2) = chi(q) / chi(-q) = psi(q) / psi(-q) = f(q) / f(-q) where phi{}, chi(), psi(), f() are Ramanujan theta functions.
G.f.: A(x) = exp( 2*sum_{n>=0} sigma(2*n+1)/(2*n+1)*x^(2*n+1) ). - _Paul D. Hanna_, Mar 01 2004
G.f. A(x) satisfies 0 = f(A(x), A(x^3)) where f(u, v) = (u - v^3) * (v + 2*u^3) - u * (u^3 - v). - _Michael Somos_, Aug 03 2011
G.f. A(x) satisfies 0 = f(A(x), A(x^5)) where f(u, v) = (u^2 - v^2)^6 - 16 * u^2 * v^2 * (1 - u^8) * (1 - v^8). - _Michael Somos_, May 12 2011
G.f. A(x) satisfies 0 = f(A(x), A(x^7)) where f(u, v) = (1 - u^8) * (1 - v^8) - (1 - u*v)^8. - _Michael Somos_, Jan 01 2006
G.f. is a period 1 Fourier series which satisfies f(-1 / (32 t)) = 2^(-1/2) g(t) where q = exp(2 Pi i t) and g() is the g.f. for A029838. - _Michael Somos_, Aug 03 2011
a(n) = (-1)^floor(n/2) * A080015(n) = (-1)^n * A108494(n). Convolution inverse is A108494. Convolution square is A007096.
Empirical : Sum_{n>=0} exp(-Pi)^n * a(n) = 2^(1/8). - _Simon Plouffe_, Feb 20 2011
a(n) ~ Pi * BesselI(1, Pi*sqrt(n/2)) / (4*sqrt(n)) ~ exp(Pi*sqrt(n/2)) / (2^(9/4) * n^(3/4)) * (1 - 3/(4*Pi*(sqrt(2*n))) - 15/(64*Pi^2*n)). - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Aug 23 2015, extended Jan 09 2017

Simon Plouffe's empirical observations are true. Furthermore, for every positive rational p, Sum_{n>=0} exp(-Pi*sqrt(p))^n * a(n) = 1/(Sum_{n>=0} (-exp(-Pi*sqrt(p)))^n * a(n)) is an algebraic number (see the MathOverflow link).  - _Vladimir Reshetnikov_, Nov 23 2016
Sum_{n = -oo..oo} (-1)^n*x^(n*(2*n-1) ), where f(a,b) = Sum_{n = -oo..oo} a^(n*(n+1)/2)*b^(n*(n-1)/2) is Ramanujan's 2-variable theta function. - _Peter Bala_, Feb 05 2021

formula: a(n) = sum_{k=1..n} floor(g_k) where g_1=1, g_{n+1} = log_x(x^frac(g_n) - x) (n>0) at x=log(2) and frac(y) = y - floor(y). See A077468 for Mathematica program by _Robert G. Wilson v_.

A080056.name: Greedy powers of (2/Pi): sum_{n=1..inf} (2/Pi)^a(n) = 1.
formula: a(n)=sum_{k=1..n}floor(g_k) where g_1=1, g_{n+1}=log_x(x^frac(g_n) - x) (n>0) at x=(2/Pi) and frac(y) = y - floor(y). See A077468 for mathematica program by _Robert G. Wilson v_.

A080057.name: Greedy powers of (e^-Gamma): sum_{n=1..inf} (e^-Gamma)^a(n) = 1, where e^-Gamma = e^(-.57721566490153286...) = .561459483566885169...
formula: a(n)=sum_{k=1..n}floor(g_k) where g_1=1, g_{n+1}=log_x(x^frac(g_n) - x) (n>0) at x=(e^-Gamma) and frac(y) = y - floor(y). See A077468 for mathematica program by _Robert G. Wilson v_.

A080058.name: Greedy powers of (1/zeta(2)): sum_{n=1..inf} (1/zeta(2))^a(n) = 1, where 1/zeta(2) = 6/Pi^2 = .607927101854...
formula: a(n)=sum_{k=1..n}floor(g_k) where g_1=1, g_{n+1}=log_x(x^frac(g_n) - x) (n>0) at x=(1/zeta(2)) and frac(y) = y - floor(y). See A077468 for mathematica program by _Robert G. Wilson v_.

A080059.name: Greedy powers of (1/zeta(3)): sum_{n=1..inf} (1/zeta(3))^a(n) = 1, where 1/zeta(3) = .83190737258070746868...
formula: a(n)=sum_{k=1..n}floor(g_k) where g_1=1, g_{n+1}=log_x(x^frac(g_n) - x) (n>0) at x=(1/zeta(3)) and frac(y) = y - floor(y). See A077468 for mathematica program by _Robert G. Wilson v_.

A080075.name: Proth numbers: of the form k*2^m + 1 for k odd, m >= 1 and 2^m > k.
formula: a(n) = A116882(n+1)+1. - _Klaus Brockhaus_, _Georgi Guninski_ and _M. F. Hasler_, Aug 16 2010

A080076.name: Proth primes: primes of the form k*2^m + 1 with odd k < 2^m, m >= 1.

A080077.name: Smallest prime p such that between p and the next prime for every k = 1, ..., n there is a number m_k whose smallest prime factor is prime(k).

A080079.name: Least number causing the longest carry sequence when adding numbers <= n to n in binary representation.
formula: a(n) = n iff n = 2^k, otherwise a(n) = A035327(n-1).
a(n) = A240769(n,1); A240769(n, a(n)) = 1. - _Reinhard Zumkeller_, Apr 13 2014

A080080.name: T(n,k) = length of longest carry sequence when adding k to n in binary representation, 1 <= k <= n (triangular array).

A080083.name: Smallest prime p such that there is a gap of 2*prime(n) between p and previous prime.

A080084.name: Number of prime factors in the factorial of the n-th prime, counted with multiplicity.
formula: a(n) = Sum_{m=1..n} Sum_{k=1..L} floor( p_n /(p_m)^k ), where L = ceiling( log(p_n)/log(p_m) ).

A080085.name: Number of factors of 2 in the factorial of the n-th prime, counted with multiplicity.
formula: a(n) = Sum_{k=1..L} floor( p_n /2^k ), where L = log(p_n)/log(2), where p_n is the n-th prime.

A080086.name: Number of factors of 3 in the factorial of the n-th prime, counted with multiplicity.
formula: a(n) = sum_{k=1..L} floor(prime(n) / 3^k), where L = log(p_n)/log(3).

A080087.name: Number of factors of 5 in the factorial of the n-th prime, counted with multiplicity.
formula: a(n) = sum_{k=1..L} floor(prime(n) /5^k), where L = log(p_n)/log(5).

A080088.name: Let r+i*s be the sum of the first-quadrant Gaussian primes dividing prime(n); sequence gives r values.

A080089.name: Let r+i*s be the sum of the first-quadrant Gaussian primes dividing prime(n); sequence gives s values.

A080090.name: a(n) is the index of the first occurrence of n in A080071, or 0 for those n>0 which never occur in A080071.

A080092.name: Irregular triangle read by rows, giving prime sequences (p-1|2n) appearing in the n-th von Staudt-Clausen sum.

A080093.name: Let sum(k>=0, k^n/(2*k+1)!) = (x(n)*e + y(n)/e)/z(n), where x(n) and z(n) are >0, then a(n)=x(n).

A080094.name: Let sum(k>=0, k^n/(2*k+1)!) = (x(n)*e + y(n)/e)/z(n), where x(n) and z(n) are >0, then a(n)=y(n).

A080095.name: Let sum(k>=0, k^n/(2*k+1)!) = (x(n)*e + y(n)/e)/z(n), where x(n) and z(n) are >0, then a(n)=z(n).

A080096.name: a(1)=a(2)=1; a(3)=2; a(n)=abs(a(n-1)-a(n-2)-a(n-3)).
formula: For n>=3 Max( a(k) : 1<=k<=n ) = floor ( sqrt(n+4)).

A080097.name: a(n) = Fibonacci(n+2)^2 - 1.
formula: If n is odd, then a(n) = F(n+1)*F(n+3) = F(n)*F(n+4) - 2, else a(n) = F(n)*F(n+4) = F(n+1)*F(n+3) - 2, where F(n) = Fibonacci numbers (A000045).
O.g.f.: x*(3-x)/((1-x^2)*(1-3*x+x^2)) (see a comment on A080144). - _Wolfdieter Lang_, Jul 30 2012
Sum_{n>=1} 1/a(n) = (43 - 15*sqrt(5))/18 = 29/9 - 5*phi/3, where phi is the golden ratio (A001622). - _Amiram Eldar_, Oct 20 2020

A080098.name: Triangle T(n,k) = n OR k, 0<=k<=n, bitwise logical OR, read by rows.

A080099.name: Triangle T(n,k) = n AND k, 0<=k<=n, bitwise logical AND, read by rows.

A080100.name: a(n) = 2^(number of 0's in binary representation of n).
formula: a(2n) = 2a(n), n>0. a(2n+1) = a(n). - _Ralf Stephan_, Apr 29 2003
a(n) = sum(k=0, n, C(n+k, k) mod 2). - _Benoit Cloitre_, Mar 06 2004
a(n) = sum(k=0, n, C(2n-k, n) mod 2). - _Paul Barry_, Dec 13 2004
G.f. satisfies: A(x) = Sum_{n>=0} [A(x)^n (mod 2)]*x^n, where A(x)^n (mod 2) reduces all coefficients modulo 2 to {0,1}. - _Paul D. Hanna_, Nov 14 2012

A080102.name: Smallest prime power in all composite numbers between n-th prime and next prime, a(n)=1 if no such prime power exists.

A080103.name: Greatest prime power in all composite numbers between n-th prime and next prime, a(n)=1 if no such prime power exists.

A080104.name: Le Corbusier's "modular" (or "modulor") numbers, based on the proportions of an ideal man.
formula: Can be obtained as a segment from the union of the two sequences 113*phi^m and 226*phi^m, m >= -13 (cf. A080105, A080106, A080078).

A080107.name: Number of fixed points of permutation of SetPartitions under {1,2,...,n}->{n,n-1,...,1}. Number of symmetric arrangements of non-attacking rooks on upper half of n X n chessboard.
formula: Knuth gives recurrences and generating functions.
a(n) = Sum_{k=0..t(n)} (-1)^k*A125810(n,k) where A125810 is a triangle of coefficients for a q-analog of the Bell numbers and t(n)=A125811(n)-1. - _Paul D. Hanna_, Jan 19 2009
a(n) = [n==0 mod 2]*Sum_{k=0..n/2} Stirling2(n/2, k)*A005425(k) + [n==1 mod 2] * Sum_{k=1..(n+1)/2} Stirling2((n+1)/2, k) * A005425(k-1). (from Knuth reference)

A080109.name: Square of primes of the form 4k+1 (A002144).

A080116.name: Characteristic function of A014486. a(n) = 1 if n's binary expansion is totally balanced, otherwise zero.

A080117.name: Binary encoding of quadratic residue set formed for n-th prime, coerced to "complementarily symmetric binary sequence" with A080261 if the prime is of the form 4k+1.

A080120.name: Dyck path encodings of Legendre's candelabras formed for primes in A080114. (I.e., symmetric rooted plane trees constructed from their quadratic residue sets.)

formula: If A058064(n) > 0, then a(n) = A058064(n). - _Max Alekseyev_, Sep 10 2020

A080123.name: Number of primes less than n*10^14.

formula: Equals Lim_{k->oo} log(k) * Product_{p prime <= k} (1 - 1/p). - _Amiram Eldar_, Jul 09 2020

A080138.name: Least positive integer multiples of angle x such that their direction cosines form a unit vector: sum(k>0, cos(a(k)*x)^2)=1, where a(1)=1 and x=3.

A080139.name: Least positive integer multiples of angle x such that their direction cosines form a unit vector: sum(k>0, cos(a(k)*x)^2)=1, where a(1)=1, a(n+1)>a(n) and x=3-Pi/2.

A080140.name: Least positive integer multiples of angle x such that their direction cosines form a unit vector: sum(k>0, cos(a(k)*x)^2)=1, where a(1)=1 and x=(2/3).

A080141.name: (3^(n-1))*(n!)^2.
formula: Expression as an n-th moment of a positive function on a positive half-axis, in Maple notation a(n)=int(x^n*2*BesselK(0, 2*sqrt(x)/sqrt(3))/9, x=0..infinity), n=1, 2... . This is a solution of a Stieltjes moment problem.

A080142.name: Greedy frac multiples of 1/Pi: a(1)=1, sum(n>0,frac(a(n)*x))=1 at x=1/Pi, where "frac(y)" denotes the fractional part of y.

A080143.name: a(n) = F(3)*F(n)*F(n+1) + F(4)*F(n+1)^2 - F(4) if n even, F(3)*F(n)*F(n+1) + F(4)*F(n+1)^2 if n odd, where F(n) is the n-th Fibonacci number (A000045).
formula: G.f.: x*(5-2*x)/((1-x^2)*(1-3*x+x^2)), see a comment on A080144 for A(4,x). - _Wolfdieter Lang_, Jul 30 2012

a(n) = (3*A027941(n) + 7*A001654(n))/2, n >= 0. Proof: from the preceding sum given by B. Cloitre via recurrence on the first factor under the sum. See also A080097 and A059840(n+2). - _Wolfdieter Lang_, Jul 27 2012

A080144.name: a(n) = F(4)*F(n)*F(n+1) + F(5)*F(n+1)^2 if n odd, a(n) = F(4)*F(n)*F(n+1) + F(5)*F(n+1)^2 - F(5) if n even, where F(n) is the n-th Fibonacci number (A000045).
formula: G.f.: x*(8-3*x)/((1-x^2)*(1-3*x+x^2)) (see the comment section). - _Wolfdieter Lang_, Jul 30 2012
a(n) = (5*A027941(n) + 11*A001654(n))/2, n >= 0. See A080143 and A080097. See the comment section for the general formula for such sums. - _Wolfdieter Lang_, Jul 27 2012

A080145.name: a(n) = Sum_{m=1..n} Sum_{i=1..m} F(i)F(i+1) where F(n)=Fibonacci numbers A000045.

A080146.name: Binary encoding of quadratic residue set for each prime. a(n) = A055094(A000040(n)).

A080147.name: Positions of primes of the form 4*k+1 (A002144) among all primes (A000040).
formula: Numbers k such that prime(k) AND 2 = 0. - _Gary Detlefs_, Dec 26 2011

A080148.name: Positions of primes of the form 4*k+3 (A002145) among all primes (A000040).

A080149.name: Numbers k such that k^2 + 1 and k^2 + 3 are both prime.
formula: Conjecture: a(n) is asymptotic to c*n*log(n)^2 with c around 2.9... - _Benoit Cloitre_, Apr 16 2004

A080150.name: Let m = Wonderful Demlo number A002477(n); a(n) = square of the sum of digits of m.

A080151.name: Let m = Wonderful Demlo number A002477(n); a(n) = sum of digits of m.
formula: a(n) = (9^2)*(n/9 - {n/9} + {n/9}^2) = 81*(floor(n/9) + {n/9}^2), where the symbol {n} means fractional part of n. - _Enrique Pérez Herrero_, Nov 22 2009

A080152.name: Values of n corresponding to the primes given in A073640. The concatenation of the a(n) and a(n+1)th primes for any n is also prime.
formula: A073640(n) = prime(a(n)), with a(n) the n-th term in this sequence.

A080153.name: a(1)=2, a(2)=3; a(n) for n>2 is the first prime > a(n-1) such that the concatenation of a(n-1), a(n-2) and a(n) is also prime.

A080154.name: Values of n corresponding to the terms in sequence A080153.
formula: For each term a(n) in this sequence, A080153(n) = prime(a(n)).

A080155.name: a(1)=2; a(n) for n>1 is the smallest prime number > a(n-1) such that the concatenation of all previous terms is also prime.
formula: For any n>1, a(n) is prime and a(n) > a(n-1). a(n) is the smallest prime for which a(1)//a(2)//...//a(n) is prime. // denotes concatenation.

A080156.name: Values of n corresponding to the terms in sequence A080155. For any k, the concatenation of the a(1) to a(k)-th primes is prime and each value of k is the smallest for which this is true.

A080157.name: Greedy frac multiples of gamma: a(1)=1, sum(n>0,frac(a(n)*x))=1 at x=gamma, where "frac(y)" denotes the fractional part of y.

A080158.name: Greedy frac multiples of Catalan's constant, G: a(1)=1, sum(n>0,frac(a(n)*x))=1 at x=G, where "frac(y)" denotes the fractional part of y.

A080159.name: Triangular array of ways of drawing k non-intersecting chords between n points on a circle; i.e., Motzkin polynomial coefficients.

A080160.name: Consider those Wonderful Demlo numbers A002477 whose digit sums are squares; sequence gives these digit sums.

A080161.name: Indices of Wonderful Demlo numbers A002477 whose digit sums are squares.

A080162.name: Wonderful Demlo numbers A002477 whose digit sums are squares.

A080163.name: Sum of an infinite series: a(n) = Sum_{k>=0} ((k+1)*(k+2))^n/(16*(2^k)).

A080164.name: Wythoff difference array, D={d(i,j)}, by antidiagonals.
formula: d(i, j)=[i*tau]F(2j-1)+(i-1)F(2j-2), where F=A000045 (Fibonacci numbers). d(i, j)=[tau*d(i, j-1)]+d(i, j-1) for i>=2. d(i, j)=3d(i, j-1)-d(i, j-2) for i>=3.

A080165.name: Primes having initial digits "10" in binary representation.

A080166.name: Primes having initial digits "11" in binary representation.

A080167.name: Primes beginning with '10' and ending with '01' in binary representation.

A080168.name: Primes beginning and ending with '11' in binary representation.

A080169.name: Numbers that are cubes of primes of the form 4k+1 (A002144).

A080170.name: Numbers k such that gcd(C(2*k,k), C(3*k,k), C(4*k,k), ..., C((k+1)*k,k) ) = 1.

A080172.name: Final digit of n-th Mersenne prime A000668(n).

A080173.name: Final 2 digits of n-th Mersenne prime A000668(n).

A080174.name: Primes p(k) such that p(k)*k falls between twin primes.

A080175.name: Fourth power of primes of the form 4k+1 (A002144).

A080176.name: Generalized Fermat numbers: 10^(2^n) + 1, n >= 0.
formula: a(n) = 9*a(n-1)*a(n-2)*...*a(1)*a(0) + 2, n >= 0, where for n = 0, we get 9*(empty product, i.e., 1)+ 2 = 11 = a(0). - _Daniel Forgues_, Jun 20 2011

A080177.name: Non-palindromic primes which on subtracting their reversal give perfect squares.

A080178.name: Non-palindromic primes which on subtracting their reversal gives perfect cubes.

A080179.name: Numbers which on adding their reversal gives perfect cubes.

A080180.name: a(1)=1, a(n+1)=a(n)+spf(Sum(a(i): 1<=i<=n)), where spf=A020639 (smallest prime factor).

A080182.name: a(1) = 1, a(n+1) = a(n) + gpf(Sum_{i=1..n} a(i)), where gpf=A006530 (greatest prime factor).

A080185.name: Primes p such that 5 is the largest of all prime factors of the numbers between p and the next prime (cf. A052248).

A080186.name: Primes p such that 7 is the largest of all prime factors of the numbers between p and the next prime (cf. A052248).

A080187.name: Primes p such that 11 is the largest of all prime factors of the numbers between p and the next prime (cf. A052248).

A080188.name: Primes p such that 13 is the largest of all prime factors of the numbers between p and the next prime (cf. A052248).

A080189.name: a(n) = k such that f^k(prime(n)) = 2, where f is the mapping of primes > 2 to primes defined by A052248.

A080190.name: Smallest prime p such that n applications of f lead form p to 2, where f is the mapping of primes > 2 to primes defined by A052248.

A080191.name: Primes p such that p is the largest of all prime factors of the numbers between the prime preceding 2*p and the next prime.
formula: f(precprime(2*p)) = p, where f is the mapping defined by A052248.

A080192.name: Complement of A080191 relative to A000040. Prime p is a term iff there is no prime between 2*p and 2*q, where q is the next prime after p.
formula: For all k, prime(k) = A000040(k) is a term if and only if A102820(k) = 0. - _Peter Munn_, Oct 24 2017

A080197.name: 13-smooth numbers: numbers whose prime divisors are all <= 13.

A080198.name: Least positive integer multiples of angle x such that their direction cosines form a unit vector: sum(k>0, cos(a(k)*x)^2)=1, where a(1)=1, a(n+1)>a(n) and x=(5/4).

A080199.name: a(1)=1; for n>1, a(n)=a(n-1) - 3 if n is already in the sequence, a(n)=a(n-1) + 6 otherwise.

A080200.name: Numbers that do not occur as differences between terms of the Mian-Chowla sequence A005282.

A080201.name: Numbers that do not occur as differences between terms of the Mian-Chowla variant A051788.

A080202.name: Triangle T(b,k) read by rows, giving numbers of pairs of unequal permutations of all the digits 1, ..., k in base b (k<b) whose ratio is an integer.

A080203.name: Steffi sequence; the numbers of pairs of unequal permutations of all the digits 1, ..., b-1 in base b whose ratio is an integer.

A080204.name: Number of fixed points under n-fold inflation for the substitution rule a->abc, b->ab, c->b that underlies the Kolakoski (3,1) sequence.
formula: Obtained from dynamical zeta function Z(x)=(1-x)/(1-2x-x^3), so that x Z'(x)/Z(x) is the ordinary power series generating function.
a(n) = n*Sum_{m=1..n} Sum_{i=0..(n-m)/2} binomial(m,i)*binomial(n-2*i-1,m-1)/m. - _Vladimir Kruchinin_, Mar 10 2015
a(n) = w1^n + w2^n + w3^n - 1, for w1, w2, w3 roots of x^3-2x^2-1=0. - _Greg Dresden_, Feb 18 2020

A080205.name: Maximal number of rational points that a (smooth, geometrically irreducible) curve of genus 3 over the finite field GF(n) can have, or 0 if n is not a prime power.

A080206.name: a(1)=a(2)=a(3)=1; a(n)=|a(n-2)+a(n-3)|-2*a(n-1).
formula: Let c=4.181943336... be the largest positive root of 1-x-4*x^2+x^3. Then a(2n) is asymptotic to a*c^n, where a=-0.0493553440330328..., while a(2n+1) is asymptotic to b*c^n, where b= 0.11422175750398... (-a/b is the smallest root (in absolute value) of 3-12*x+13*x^2-3*x^3.)

limit n ->infinity a(2n+1)/a(2n)=-2.3142733525986128..., the largest root (in absolute value) of 3+13*x+12*x^2+3*x^3; limit n ->infinity a(2n)/a(2n-1)=-1.8070222... the largest root (in absolute value) of -3+3*x+8*x^2+3*x^3.

A080207.name: Let F(x) = 1 + x + 4x^2 + 9x^3 + ... = g.f. for A002835 (solid partitions restricted to two planes) and write F(x) = 1/Product_{n>=1} (1-x^n)^a(n).

A080208.name: a(n) is the least k such that the generalized Fermat number (k+1)^(2^n) + k^(2^n) is prime.

A080209.name: Gilbreath transform of the sequence of Sophie Germain primes (A005384), i.e., the diagonal of leading successive absolute differences of A005384.

A080210.name: Lower bound for the multiplicity of a disjoint covering system of congruences.
formula: a(n) = floor(Lpf(n)*phi(n)/n) + 1 where Lpf(n) is the largest prime factor of n and phi is the Euler totient function.

A080211.name: a(n) = binomial(n, smallest prime factor of n).

A080212.name: Binomial(n, smallest odd prime factor of n).

A080213.name: a(n) = binomial(n, greatest prime factor of n).

A080214.name: Binomial(greatest prime factor of n, smallest prime factor of n).

A080215.name: Binomial(greatest prime factor of n, smallest odd prime factor of n).

A080216.name: a(n) is the largest value taken by binomial(n,j) mod j for j in [1..n].

A080217.name: a(n) is the number of distinct values taken by binomial(n,j) mod j for j in [1..n].

A080218.name: Monotonically increasing sequence such that every positive integer n appears if and only if d(n) doesn't (d(n)=number of divisors of n, A000005).

A080219.name: Decimal expansion of exponential factorial constant Sum_{n>=1} 1/A049384(n).

A080220.name: a(1)=2; then if n is prime, a(n) is the smallest prime number greater than a(n-1), if n is composite a(n)=a(n-1)+1.
formula: There is a constant C such that limit n ->infinity a(n)/n = C =1.72...

A080221.name: n is Harshad (divisible by the sum of its digits) in a(n) bases from 1 to n.

A080222.name: Record-setting differences between adjacent elements of the Mian-Chowla sequence A005282.

A080223.name: Record-setting differences between adjacent elements of the Mian-Chowla sequence variant A051788.

A080224.name: Number of abundant divisors of n.

A080225.name: Number of perfect divisors of n.

A080226.name: Number of deficient divisors of n.
formula: a(n) = Sum_{d|n} A294934(d) = A294926(n) + A294934(n). - _Antti Karttunen_, Nov 14 2017

A080228.name: Numbers containing the digits 0, 1, 2, 5 or 8 only.

A080229.name: Number of terms in the continued fraction for x, where x is the Golden ratio (phi=(1+sqrt(5))/2) truncated to n decimal digits.

A080230.name: Engel expansion for (positive) constant defined in A078756.
formula: See A006784 for definition of Engel expansion

A080231.name: Engel expansion for (negative) constant defined in A078756.
formula: See A006784 for definition of Engel expansion

A080232.name: Triangle T(n,k) of differences of pairs of consecutive terms of triangle A071919.
formula: T(n, k) = binomial(n, k) + 2*Sum{j=1...k} (-1)^j binomial(n, k-j).
Sum_{k=0..n} T(n, k)*x^k = (1-x)*(1+x)^(n-1), for n >= 1. - _Philippe Deléham_, Sep 05 2005
T(n,k) = T(n-1,k-1) + T(n-1,k) with T(n,0)=1, T(n,n)=-1 for n > 0. - _Philippe Deléham_, Nov 01 2011
T(n,k)  =binomial(n-1,k) - binomial(n-1,k-1), for n > 0. T(n,k) = Sum_{i=-k..k} (-1)^i*binomial(n-1,k+i)*binomial(n+1,k-i), for n >= k. T(n,k)=0, for n < k. - _Mircea Merca_, Apr 28 2012

A080233.name: Triangle T(n,k) obtained by taking differences of consecutive pairs of row elements of Pascal's triangle A007318.
formula: T(n, k) = if(k>n, 0, binomial(n, k)-binomial(n, k-1)).

A080234.name: Triangle whose rows are the differences of consecutive pairs of row elements of A080232.

A080235.name: Number of terms in the continued fraction for (Pi truncated to n decimal digits).

A080236.name: Triangle of differences of consecutive pairs of row elements of triangle A080233.

A080237.name: Start with 1 and apply the process: k-th run is 1, 2, 3, ..., a(k-1)+1.
formula: It seems that Sum_{k=1..n} a(k) = C*n*log(log(n)) + O(n*log(log(n))) with C = 0.6....
a(n) = A007814(A014486(n)) (i.e., number of trailing zeros in A063171(n)).

A080238.name: Largest squarefree number dividing sum of cubes of divisors of n.

A080239.name: Antidiagonal sums of triangle A035317.
formula: a(n) = Sum_{j=0..floor(n/2)} Sum_{k=0..floor((n-j)/2)} binomial(n-j-2k, j-2k} for n>=0.
Another recurrence is given in the Maple code.
If n mod 4 = 1 then a(n) = a(n-1) + a(n-2) + 1, else a(n)= a(n-1) + a(n-2). - _Gary Detlefs_, Dec 05 2010
a(n+1) = a(n) + a(n-1) + A011765(n+1). - _Reinhard Zumkeller_, Jan 06 2012
a(n) = Sum_{k=0..floor((n-1)/4)} Fibonacci(n-4*k). - _Johannes W. Meijer_, Apr 19 2012

A080240.name: Define two sequences by A_n = mex{A_i,B_i : 0 <= i < n} for n >= 0, B_0=0, B_1=1 and for n >= 2, B_n = 2B_{n-1}+(-1)^{A_n}. Sequence gives A_n.

A080241.name: Define two sequences by A_n = mex{A_i,B_i : 0 <= i < n} for n >= 0, B_0=0, B_1=1 and for n >= 2, B_n = 2B_{n-1}+(-1)^{A_n}. Sequence gives B_n.

A080242.name: Table of coefficients of polynomials P(n,x) defined by the relation P(n,x) = (1+x)*P(n-1,x) + (-x)^(n+1).
formula: The polynomials P(n,-x), n > 0, satisfy a Riemann hypothesis: their zeros lie on the vertical line Re x = 1/2 in the complex plane.

T(n,k) = if(k<=2*floor((n+1)/2), Sum_{j=0..floor((n+1)/2)} binomial(n-2j,k-2j), 0). - _Paul Barry_, Apr 08 2011 (This formula produces the odd numbered rows correctly, but not the even. - _G. C. Greubel_, Feb 22 2019)

A080243.name: Signed super-Catalan or little Schroeder numbers.
formula: G.f.: 1 - x/(Q(0) + x) where Q(k) = 1 + k*(1+x) + x + x*(k+1)*(k+2)/Q(k+1); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Mar 14 2013
G.f. A(x) satisfies: A(x) = (1 - 2*x*A(x)^2) / (1 - x). - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Jun 30 2020

A080245.name: Inverse of coordination sequence array A113413.
formula: Essentially the same as the triangle T(n, k), for n>0 and k>0, given by [0, -2, -1, -2, -1, -2, -1, -2, ...] DELTA A000007. Triangle (unsigned) given by [0, 2, 1, 2, 1, 2, 1, 2, ...] DELTA A000007, where DELTA is Deléham's operator defined in A084938.

A080247.name: Formal inverse of triangle A080246. Unsigned version of A080245.
formula: Essentially same triangle as triangle T(n,k), n > 0 and k > 0, read by rows; given by [0, 2, 1, 2, 1, 2, 1, 2, 1, 2, ...] DELTA A000007 where DELTA is Deléham's operator defined in A084938.
T(n, k) = T(n-1, k-1) + 2*Sum_{j>=0} T(n-1, k+j) with T(0, 0) = 1 and T(n, k)=0 if k < 0. - _Philippe Deléham_, Jan 19 2004
T(n, k) = (k+1)*Sum_{j=0..n-k} (binomial(n+1, k+j+1)*binomial(n+j, j))/(n+1). - _Emeric Deutsch_, May 31 2004
Recurrence: T(0,0)=1; T(n,k) = T(n-1,k-1) + T(n-1,k) + T(n,k+1). - _David Callan_, Jul 03 2006
T(n, k) = binomial(n, k)*hypergeom([k - n, n + 1], [k + 2], -1). - _Peter Luschny_, Jan 08 2018

A080248.name: Stirling-like number triangle defined by sequence A000217.
formula: Columns are generated by 1/Product_{k=1..n+1} (1 - C(k + 1, 2)*x). [In other words:
T(n, k) = (k*(k+1)/2) * T(n-1,k) + T(n-1,k-1), T(n,n)=1. - _Vladimir Kruchinin_, Aug 25 2020

The polynomials p(n,x) = Sum_{k=0..n} T(n,k) * (k!*(k+1)!/2^k) * x^(k+2) satisfy for n >= 0 the equations p(n+1,x) = p(1,x) * p''(n,x) / 2 and p(n,-1) = 0^n when p'' is the second derivative of p. - _Werner Schulte_, Dec 15 2020

A080249.name: Stirling-like number triangle defined by the sequence A000292=C(n+3,3).
formula: T(n,k) = T(n-1,k-1) + A000292(k)*T(n-1,k). Columns are generated by 1/product{k=0..n, 1-C(k+3,3)*x}.

A080251.name: Paired decomposition of tetrahedral numbers A000292 arranged as number triangle.
formula: Also generated by the product of pairs of integers 0 <= r1,r2 <= n whose sum is n+2.
Viewed as a square array: T(n,2*k) = k*(k+n); T(n,2*k+1) = (k+1)*(k+n). - _Luc Rousseau_, Dec 11 2017

A080253.name: a(n) is the number of elements in the Coxeter complex of type B_n (or C_n).
formula: E.g.f: exp(x)/(2-exp(2*x)). - Antonio G. Astudillo (afg_astudillo(AT)hotmail.com), Feb 14 2003
a(n) = sum(binomial(n, t)*2^(n-t)*A000670(n-t), t=0..n); # Fishburn 2001, p. 57.
a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n} Stirling2(n, k)*k!*A001333(k+1). - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Sep 28 2003

An approximation formula can be derived from the latter, a(n) ~ n!/(2*sqrt(2))*(2/log(2))^(n+1), with relative errors approaching asymptotically zero as n increases. - _Gerson Washiski Barbosa_, Jun 26 2009
Half the row sums of triangle A154695. - _Gerson Washiski Barbosa_, Jun 26 2009
G.f.: 1 + x/G(0) where G(k) = 1 - x*3*(2*k+1) + x^2*(k+1)*(k+1)*(1-3^2)/G(k+1); (continued fraction due to Stieltjes). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Jan 11 2013
a(n) = sum_{k = 0..n} A060187(n, k)*2^(n-k). - _Peter Luschny_, Apr 26 2013
G.f.: 1/Q(0), where Q(k) = 1 - 3*x*(2*k+1) - 8*x^2*(k+1)^2/Q(k+1); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Sep 28 2013
a(n) = log(2) * int {x = 0..inf} (2*floor(x) + 1)^n * 2^(-x) dx. - _Peter Bala_, Feb 06 2015
a(n) = (-1)^(n+1)*(Li_{-n}(sqrt(2)) - Li_{-n}(-sqrt(2)))/(2*sqrt(2)), where Li_n(x) is the polylogarithm.

A080254.name: For n>3, a(n) is the number of elements in the Coxeter complex of type D_n (although the sequence starts at n=0. See comments below for precise explanation).
formula: a(0)=a(1)=1. For n>1, a(n)=1 + sum('2^r*binomial(n, r)*a(n-r)', 'r'=1..n)

A080255.name: Antisquares: of the form a*p^k where p is prime, k is odd and a is nonsquare modulo p.

A080256.name: Sum of numbers of distinct and of all prime factors of n.

A080257.name: Numbers having at least two distinct or a total of at least three prime factors.
formula: a(n) = n + O(n/log n). - _Charles R Greathouse IV_, Sep 14 2015

A080258.name: Either 4th power of a prime, or product of a prime and the square of a different prime.

A080259.name: Numbers whose squarefree kernel is not a primorial number, i.e., A007947(a(n)) is not in A002110.

A080261.name: Simple involution of natural numbers: complement [binary_width(n)/2] least significant bits in the binary expansion of n.

A080262.name: Cunningham numbers: of the form a^b +- 1, where a, b >= 2.

A080263.name: A014486-encoding of the branch-reduced binomial-mod-2 binary trees.

A080264.name: A063171-encoding of the stunted binomial-mod-2 zigzag trees. See A080263.

A080265.name: A014486-index of the stunted binomial-mod-2 zigzag trees. See A080263.

A080267.name: a(n) = Sum_{d divides n} d*2^(n-n/d).
formula: G.f. Sum( k*2^(k-1)*x^k/(1-2^(k-1)*x^k), k=1..infinity). - _N. J. A. Sloane_, Jun 04 2003

A080268.name: Breadth-first-wise A014486-like encoding of the stunted binomial-mod-2 zigzag trees (A080263).

A080269.name: Breadth-first-wise A063171-like-encoding of the stunted binomial-mod-2 zigzag trees (A080264).

A080272.name: Orbit size of each tree A080263(n) under Donaghey's "Map M" Catalan automorphism.

A080273.name: Orbit size of each tree A080263(n) under Meeussen's bf<->df map on binary trees.

A080274.name: Orbit size of each complete binary tree under Meeussen's bf<->df map on binary trees.

A080276.name: Variation on Connell sequence (A001614). In this one, a(1)=1, terms a(n) onwards are generated in "blocks" as the next a(n-1) odd numbers > a(n-1) if the previous block ends with a(n-1) even and the next a(n-1) even numbers > a(n-1) if the previous block ends with a(n-1) odd.
formula: a(n) = round( LambertW(3^((4*n-3)/2)*log(3)/2)/log(3)) = round( LambertW(x*exp((4*n-3)*x))/(2*x) ), where x=log(sqrt(3)). - Antonio G. Astudillo (afg_astudillo(AT)hotmail.com), Feb 13 2003

A080277.name: Partial sums of A038712.
formula: a(n) is conjectured to be asymptotic to n*log(n)/log(2). - _Klaus Brockhaus_, Mar 23 2003 [See Bannister et al., 2013. - _N. J. A. Sloane_, Nov 26 2013]

Product_{n >= 1} (1 + x^(n*2^(n-1)) = (1 + x)*(1 + x^4)*(1 + x^12)*(1 + x^32)*... = 1 + Sum_{n >= 1} x^a(n) = 1 + x + x^4 + x^5 + x^12 + x^13 + .... Hence this sequence lists the numbers representable as a sum of distinct elements of A001787 = [1, 4, 12, ..., n*2^(n-1), ...]. Cf. A050292. See also A120385. - _Peter Bala_, Feb 02 2013
n log_2 n - 2n < a(n) <= n log_2 n + n [Bannister et al., 2013] - _David Eppstein_, Aug 31 2013
G.f. A(x) satisfies: A(x) = 2*A(x^2)*(1 + x) + x/(1 - x)^2. - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Oct 30 2019

A080278.name: a(n) = (3^(v_3(n) + 1) - 1)/2, where v_3(n) = highest power of 3 dividing n = A007949(n).
formula: L.g.f.: -log(Product_{k>=0} (1 - x^(3^k))) = Sum_{n>=1} a(n)*x^n/n. - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Mar 15 2018

A080279.name: Numbers n such that 1/G^n is closer to its nearest integer than any value of 1/G^k for 1 <= k < n, where G is Catalan's constant.

A080280.name: Numbers n such that Pi^(n*e)-e^n is closer to its nearest integer than any value of Pi^(k*e)-e^k for 1 <= k < n.

A080281.name: Numbers k such that Pi^k - 1/phi is closer to its nearest integer than any value of Pi^j - 1/phi for 1 <= j < k.

A080282.name: Numbers n such that log(n) + log_10(n) is closer to its nearest integer than any value of log(k) + log_10(k) for 1 < = k < n.

A080283.name: Numbers n such that (log(n)/Pi)^2 is closer to its nearest integer than any value of (log(k)/Pi)^2 for 1 <= k < n.

A080284.name: Numbers n such that (Pi/e)^n is closer to its nearest integer than any value of (Pi/e)^k for 1 <= k < n.

A080285.name: Numbers n such that [(Pi+e)/(Pi-e)]^n is closer to its nearest integer than any value of [(Pi+e)/(Pi-e)]^k for 1 <= k < n.

A080286.name: Numbers n such that (Pi+e)^n is closer to its nearest integer than any value of (Pi+e)^k for 1 <= k < n.

A080287.name: Successively larger gaps in Ulam numbers start at this Ulam number.

A080288.name: Successively larger gaps between Ulam numbers.

A080289.name: Integers n for which the ratio phi(n)/pi(n) is smaller than for any subsequent n. Here phi(n) is Euler's totient function and pi(n) is the number of primes that are at most n.

A080292.name: Orbit size of each tree A080293(n) under Donaghey's "Map M" Catalan automorphism.

A080293.name: A014486-encoding of the branch-reduced binomial-mod-2 binary trees.

A080294.name: A063171-encoding of the branch-reduced binomial-mod-2 binary trees.

A080295.name: A014486-index of the branch-reduced binomial-mod-2 binary trees.

A080297.name: Orbit size of each tree A080293(n) under Meeussen's bf<->df map on binary trees.

A080299.name: A014486-encoding of plane binary trees (Stanley's d) whose interior zigzag-tree (Stanley's c, i.e., tree obtained by discarding the outermost edges of the binary tree) is isomorphic to a valid plane binary tree (Stanley's d).

A080300.name: Global ranking function for totally balanced binary sequences.

A080301.name: Local ranking function for totally balanced binary sequences: if n's binary expansion is totally balanced (A080116(n)=1), then a(n) is its zero-based position among A000108((A000523(n)+1)/2) lexicographically ordered totally balanced binary sequences of the same width, otherwise -1.

A080303.name: Rewrite 0->100 in the binary expansion of n.

A080304.name: Numerator of n^mu(n), where mu is the Moebius function (A008683).
formula: a(n) = if mu(n)>0 then n else 1.

A080305.name: Denominator of n^mu(n), where mu is the Moebius function (A008683).
formula: a(n) = if mu(n)<0 then n else 1, where mu is Moebius mu function (A008683).

A080306.name: Numerator of Sum(k^mu(k): 1<=k<=n), where mu is the Moebius function (A008683).

A080309.name: n-th even number equals n-th multiple of a Fermat number.

A080310.name: Rewrite 0->100 in the binary expansion of n (but leaving single zero as zero) and append 10 to the right.

A080311.name: Orbit size of each tree encoded by A014486(n) under Meeussen's bf<->df map on binary trees.

A080316.name: a(n) = A080315(n) - 2^A000523(A080315(n)), i.e., the terms of A080315 without their most significant bit.

A080318.name: Breadth-first-wise A014486-like encoding of the branch-reduced binomial-mod-2 binary trees (A080293).

A080319.name: Breadth-first-wise A063171-like-encoding of the branch-reduced binomial-mod-2 binary trees (A080294).

A080322.name: Determinant of the n X n tridiagonal matrix M with the elements on the diagonals equal to 1, except M(n,n-1)=M(n-1,n)=n.
formula: a(3*k+1) = (-1)^k, where k is an integer >= 1.

A080323.name: a(n) = mu(n)^n, where mu is the Moebius function (A008683).

A080324.name: Union of even squarefree numbers (A001747) and squarefree numbers for which the number of prime factors is even (A030229).

A080325.name: Multiple of coefficients in expansion of 1/sin(x)^2.

A080326.name: Denominator of Sum(k^mu(k): 1<=k<=n), where mu is the Moebius function (A008683).

A080327.name: Numbers n for which Lucas(n) and Fibonacci(n) are both prime.

A080328.name: Smaller of the two Ulam numbers that sum to the n-th Ulam number.

A080329.name: Larger of the two Ulam numbers that sum to the n-th Ulam number.

A080330.name: Index in A002858 of the smaller of the two Ulam numbers that sum to the n-th Ulam number.

A080331.name: Index in A002858 of the larger of the two Ulam numbers that sum to the n-th Ulam number.

A080332.name: G.f.: Product_{n>0} (1 - x^n)^3 * (1 - x^(2*n - 1))^2 = Sum_{n in Z} (6*n + 1) * x^(n*(3*n + 1)/2).
formula: Expansion of f(-x)^2 * phi(x) = f(-x^2) * phi(-x^2)^2 in powers of x^2 where phi(), f() are Ramanujan theta functions. - _Michael Somos_, Feb 18 2003
Expansion of q^(-1/24) * eta(q)^5 / eta(q^2)^2 in powers of q.
Euler transform of period 2 sequence [-5, -3, ...]. - _Michael Somos_, Sep 09 2007

a(n) = b(24*n + 1) where b(n) is multiplicative with b(2^e) = 0^e, b(3^e) = 0^e, b(p^e) = (1+(-1)^e)/2* p^(e/2) if p == 1 (mod 6), b(p^e) = (1+(-1)^e)/2 * (-p)^(e/2) if p == 5 (mod 6). - _Michael Somos_, May 26 2005
G.f. is a period 1 Fourier series which satisfies f(-1 / (48 t)) = 32^(1/2) (t/i)^(3/2) g(t) where q = exp(2 Pi i t) and g() is the g.f. for A113277. - _Michael Somos_, Feb 18 2003

A080333.name: Partial sums of A080278.
formula: a(n) is conjectured to be asymptotic to n*log(n)/log(3). - _Klaus Brockhaus_, Mar 23 2003 [This follows from the asymptotics of A333979. - _Pontus von Brömssen_, Sep 06 2020]

A080334.name: n^2 read backwards, for n = 51, 50, 49, ...
formula: Write the squares backwards: 1, 4, 9, 61, 52, 63, 94, 46, 18, 1, 121, 441, 961, 691, ..., then reverse the sequence.

A080335.name: Diagonal in square spiral or maze arrangement of natural numbers.
formula: E.g.f.: exp(x)*(2 + 3*x + x^2) - cosh(x). The sequence 1,1,5,9,... is given by n^2+(1+(-1)^n)/2 with e.g.f. exp(1+x+x^2)*exp(x)-sinh(x). - _Paul Barry_, Sep 02 2003 and Sep 19 2003
a(n) = A000035(n) + A000290(n+1). - _Wesley Ivan Hurt_, Oct 10 2013
a(n) = (n+1)^2 when n is even; a(n) = (n+1)^2 + 1 when n is odd.

A080337.name: Bisection of A080107.
formula: a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n} Stirling2(n, k)*A005425(k-1). (from Knuth reference) - _Robert A. Russell_, Apr 28 2018

A080338.name: Product of consecutive previous terms (starting with 2,3).

A080339.name: Characteristic function of {1} union {primes}: 1 if n is 1 or a prime, else 0.
formula: a(n) = Sum_digits{binomial(n! mod (n+1), n)}, with n >= 0. - _Paolo P. Lava_, Apr 24 2007
a(1)=1, and a(n) = Prod_{k=1...n-1}(k/n)^2 where (a/b) is the Jacobi symbol and n>1. - _Dimitri Papadopoulos_, Jan 13 2016

A080340.name: First known infinite sequence containing no odd integer of the form 2^m+p (p prime).

A080341.name: Sum of the n first terms that are congruent to 1, 4 or 5 mod 6 (A047259).
formula: a(n) = n^2+(n+1)/3 with integer division, that is n mod 3 = 0 : n^2+n/3 n mod 3 = 1 : n^2+(n-1)/3 n mod 3 = 2 : n^2+(n+1)/3.

A080342.name: Number of weighings required to identify a single bad coin out of n coins, using a two-pan balance.
formula: a(n) = floor(L) - floor(2^(-f(L))) + 1, where L = log_3(n) and f() = fractional part.

A080343.name: a(n) = round(sqrt(2*n)) - floor(sqrt(2*n)).
formula: a(n) = 1 iff n >= 4 and n is in the interval [t_k + 1, ..., t_k + floor(k/2)] for some k >= 2, where t_k = k*(k+1)/2 is a triangular number.

A080344.name: Partial sums of A023969.
formula: a(n) = (1/2)*(n + 1 - t - abs(n + 1 - t^2)), where t = floor(sqrt(n+1) + 1/2).

A080345.name: a(n) is the number of prime factors in Fibonacci(prime(n)); that is, in the Fibonacci number whose index is the n-th prime.

A080346.name: First card number to reach the top of the deck n times in Guy's shuffle (see A035485).

A080347.name: Number of shuffles in Guy's shuffle (A035485) corresponding to the terms in A080346.

A080348.name: Costé prime expansion of Catalan's constant.

A080353.name: a(1)=5; for n>1, a(n)=a(n-1)+1 if n is already in the sequence, a(n)=a(n-1)+2 otherwise.

A080356.name: Number of twin primes between n and 2n. Only smaller of twins (terms of A001359) are counted.

A080357.name: Smallest x such that between x and 2x exactly n twin prime numbers can be found.

A080358.name: Value of Vandermonde determinant for the first n prime numbers: V[p(1),...,p(n)].
formula: a(n) = Product[p(i)-p(j)]; i, j, i>j. for n, it is product of C(n, 2) prime differences of not necessarily consecutive primes.

A080359.name: The smallest integer x > 0 such that the number of primes in (x/2, x] equals n.

A080360.name: a(n) is the largest positive integer x such that the number of unitary-prime-divisors of x! equals n. Same as the largest positive integer x such that the number of primes in (x/2,x] equals n.

A080361.name: a(n) is the difference between the largest and the smallest positive integers x such that the number of unitary-prime-divisors of x! equals n. Same as the difference between the largest and the smallest positive integers x such that the number of primes in (x/2,x] equals n.

A080362.name: a(n) is the number of positive integers x such that the number of unitary-prime-divisors of x! equals n. Same as the number of positive integers x such that the number of primes in (x/2,x] equals n.

A080363.name: Nonprime numbers k such that the largest prime divisor of k is unitary.

A080364.name: Composite numbers whose least prime factor appears with multiplicity 1.

A080365.name: Composite numbers k whose smallest and largest prime factors are unitary prime factors.

A080366.name: Numbers k whose least and greatest prime divisors are non-unitary.

A080367.name: Largest unitary prime divisor of n or a(n)=0 if no such prime divisor exists.

A080368.name: a(n) is the least unitary prime divisor of n, or 0 if no such prime divisor exists.
formula: If A277697(n) = 0, then a(n) = 0, otherwise a(n) = A000040(A277697(n)). - _Antti Karttunen_, Oct 28 2016

A080369.name: a(n) is the value of Vandermonde determinant for lexicographically earliest n-mark Golomb-ruler.
formula: a(n)=Product[a(i)-a(j)], j<i<=n; product of C[n, 2] positive differences provided by the n marks of ruler.

A080370.name: Number of distinct values among the differences prime(j)-prime(i), 1 <= i < j <= n.

A080371.name: a(n) is the smallest x such that the quotient d(x+1)/d(x) equals n, where d = A000005.

A080372.name: a(n) is the smallest x such that the quotient d(x)/d(x+1) equals n, where d = A000005.

A080373.name: a(n) is the smallest number such that GCD of n values of prime(j)-1 for successive j values is greater than 2, where prime(j)=j-th prime.
formula: a(n) = Min{x; gcd[prime(x)-1, ..., prime(x+n-1)]>2}, where prime()=A000040().

A080374.name: a(n)=lcm of first n consecutive prime differences.

A080375.name: a(n)=distinct values of lcm of first n consecutive prime differences[see A080374].

A080377.name: Each a(n) is a difference of suitable consecutive primes, a(n)=Prime[1+A080376(n)]-Prime[A080376(n)]. a(n+1) is the smallest prime-difference [from A001223] which has prime-factor not present in previous terms or was present but at lower power.

A080378.name: Residues mod 4 of the n-th difference between consecutive primes.

A080379.name: Least n such that n consecutive values in A080378 equals 2; i.e., exactly n differences between consecutive primes give residues 2 when divided by 4.

A080380.name: Least n such that n consecutive values in A080378 equal 0; i.e., exactly n differences between consecutive primes are divisible by 4.

A080381.name: Triangle read by rows: gcd(binomial(n,floor(n/2)), binomial(n,i), i=0..n; greatest common divisor of binomial coefficients and corresponding central binomial coefficient.

A080382.name: Triangle read by rows: T(n,k) = C(n,floor(n/2))/gcd(C(n,floor(n/2)),C(n,k)), k=0..n; central binomial coefficient is divided by greatest common divisor of binomial coefficients and corresponding central binomial coefficient.

A080383.name: Number of j (0 <= j <= n) such that the central binomial coefficient C(n,floor(n/2)) = A001405(n) is divisible by C(n,j).

A080384.name: Numbers k such that there are exactly 6 numbers j for which binomial(k, floor(k/2)) / binomial(k,j) is an integer, i.e., A080383(k) = 6.

A080385.name: Numbers k such that there are exactly 7 numbers j for which binomial(k, floor(k/2)) / binomial(k,j) is an integer, i.e., A080383(k) = 7.

A080386.name: Numbers k such that there are exactly 8 numbers j for which binomial(k, floor(k/2)) / binomial(k,j) is an integer, i.e., A080383(k) = 8.

A080387.name: Numbers k such that there are exactly 10 numbers j for which binomial(k, floor(k/2)) / binomial(k,j) is an integer, i.e., A080383(k) = 10.

A080389.name: Numbers n such that gcd( n+1, binomial(n, floor(n/2)) ) = 1.

A080390.name: Least x such that gcd(A001405(x+1), A001405(x)) = n.

A080391.name: Number of integers among the following n+1 quotients: A001405(n)/A001405(k), k=0,..,n. Number of values k for which the n-th central binomial coefficient[cbc] is divisible by the k-th cbc-s k=0,..n.

A080392.name: Numbers k such that A000984(k) mod k = 0 and A080383(k) != 7.

A080393.name: a(n) is the smallest integer such that A080383(a(n)) = n.

A080394.name: Central binomial coefficient [A001405] is divisible by n^2.

A080395.name: Central binomial coefficient [A000984] is divisible by n^2.

A080396.name: Largest squarefree numbers dividing the binomial coefficients C(n,k) read by row, 0<=k<=n. Squarefree kernel of Pascal triangle.

A080397.name: Largest squarefree number dividing central binomial coefficient A000984(n).

A080398.name: Largest squarefree number dividing sum of divisors of n.

A080399.name: Largest squarefree number dividing sum of squares of divisors of n.

A080400.name: Largest squarefree number dividing phi of n.
formula: a(m * n) = A007947(a(m) * a(n)) if gcd(m, n) = 1. - _David A. Corneth_, Jul 16 2017

A080401.name: A001157(n) is squarefree: sum of squares of divisors of n is squarefree.

A080402.name: A001157(n) is not squarefree: sum of squares of divisors of n is not squarefree.

A080403.name: Numbers n such that both A000213(n) and A001157(n) are squarefree: sum of divisors and squares of divisors of n are squarefree.

A080404.name: a(n)=A007947[A055932(n)]; the sequence consists of primorial numbers;.

A080405.name: Number of distinct primes dividing n-th Catalan number.

A080406.name: Boustrophedon transform of the continued fraction of Pi (cf. A001203).
formula: a(n) appears to be asymptotic to C*n!*(2/Pi)^n where C=136.651536367325329682973604897976758877614262731284965133228708820... - _Benoit Cloitre_ and Mark Hudson (mrmarkhudson(AT)hotmail.com)

A080407.name: Decimal expansion of the number which results when the Boustrophedon transform of the continued fraction of Pi (A080406, A001203) is interpreted as a continued fraction.

A080408.name: Boustrophedon transform of the continued fraction of e (A003417).
formula: a(n) appears to be asymptotic to C*n!*(2/Pi)^n where C = 9.27921365277635263761227970562207183019110298580498662908878310... - _Benoit Cloitre_ and Mark Hudson (mrmarkhudson(AT)hotmail.com)

A080409.name: Decimal expansion of the number which results when the Boustrophedon transform of the continued fraction of e (A080408, A003417) is interpreted as a continued fraction.

A080410.name: Boustrophedon transform of the continued fraction of the Euler-Mascheroni constant, gamma (A001620).
formula: a(n) appears to be asymptotic to C*n!*(2/Pi)^n where C=5.79838940503783299259552225238077705314049166104773668246015... which almost satisfies the polynomial equation 94487-16249C-8C^2=0 - _Benoit Cloitre_ and Mark Hudson (mrmarkhudson(AT)hotmail.com)

A080411.name: Decimal expansion of the number which results when the Boustrophedon transform of the continued fraction of gamma (A080410) is interpreted as a continued fraction.

A080412.name: Exchange rightmost two binary digits of n > 1; a(0)=0, a(1)=2.
formula: a(n) = a(n-1) + a(n-4) - a(n-5) for n > 4. - _Joerg Arndt_, Mar 11 2013

A080413.name: Take the rightmost three binary digits of n (for n<4 padded with leading zeros) and rotate left 1 digit.

A080414.name: Take the rightmost three binary digits of n (for n<4 padded with leading zeros) and rotate right 1 digit.

A080415.name: a(n) is the number of distinct substrings in the initial string of length n of the repetition-resistant sequence A079101.

A080416.name: Stirling-like number triangle defined by paired decomposition of C(n+3,3) = A000292.
formula: Columns are generated as follows: Display C(n+3, 3) as row sums of the triangle A080251, or {1}, {2, 2}, {3, 3, 4}, {4, 4, 6, 6}, {5, 5, 8, 8, 9}, ... The columns are then generated by 1/(1-x), 1/(1-2x)^2, 1/(1-3x)^2(1-4x)), 1/((1-4x)^2(1-6x)^2)), etc.

A080417.name: Signed Stirling numbers of the second kind.

A080418.name: Generalized Pascal triangle.
formula: T(n, 1)=1, T(n, k)=0 for k>n, T(n, 2) = T(n-1, 1) + T(n-1, 2) + 2*(-1)^n, T(n, k) = T(n-1, k-1) + T(n-1, k) + (-1)^(n+k) for k>2. [corrected by _Frank M Jackson_, Mar 27 2012]

A080419.name: Triangle of generalized Chebyshev coefficients.
formula: T(n,1) = A006234(n+2), T(n,n) = 1, T(n,k) = T(n-1,k-1) + 3*T(n-1,k), T(n,k)=0 for k>n. - corrected by _Michel Marcus_, Apr 15 2018
As a square array, T1(n, k)= (n+3k)3^n Product{j=1..(k-1), n+j}/(3k(k-1)!) (k>=1, n>=0).

A080425.name: Period 3: repeat [0, 2, 1].
formula: a(n) = 2 * A001045(L(n/3)), where L(j/p) is the Legendre symbol of j and p.
a(n) = (-n) mod 3; also a(n) = 3*ceiling(n/3)-n. - _Hieronymus Fischer_, May 29 2007

A080426.name: a(1)=1, a(2)=3; all terms are either 1 or 3; each run of 3's is followed by a run of two 1's; and a(n) is the length of the n-th run of 3's.
formula: a(1) = 1; for n>1, a(n) = A003156(n) - A003156(n-1). - _Philippe Deléham_, Apr 16 2004

A080427.name: a(1)=1 and, for n>1, a(n) is the smallest positive integer such that the absolute difference |a(n)-a(n-1)| has not occurred previously.
formula: It appears that abs(a(n+2)-a(n+1)) = A101544(n) for any n > 0. - _Rémy Sigrist_, Apr 12 2020

A080429.name: Odd numbers such that all a(i)*a(j) with i<j are distinct.

A080430.name: a(n) = least odd number such that all pairwise sums a(i) + a(j), i < j <= n, are distinct.

A080431.name: Even numbers such that all a(i)*a(j) are distinct.

A080432.name: Even numbers such that all a(i) + a(j) are distinct.

A080433.name: a(1) = 2; for n>1, a(n) = smallest multiple of n beginning with the least significant digit of a(n-1) > n and not divisible by 10 if n is not of the type 10k; otherwise a(n) ends in 0 and a(n+1) begins with the first nonzero digit from the right(LSD) of a(n).

A080435.name: a(1) = 1; a(n) = least k > a(n-1) such that each prime of form a(i)+a(j) occurs for unique i <= j.

A080436.name: Smallest multiple of n obtained by inserting digits between every pair of digits of n. If n is a k-digit number then there are (k-1) places where digit insertion takes place and a(n) contains at least 2k-1 digits.

A080437.name: For n < 5, a(n) = n-th prime. For n >= 5, let m = n-th prime. If m is a k-digit prime then a(n) = smallest prime obtained by inserting at least one digit between every pair of digits of m. There are (k-1) places where digit insertion takes place and a(n) contains at least 2k-1 digits.

A080438.name: Smallest square obtained by inserting one or more digits between every pair of consecutive digits of n^2.

A080439.name: a(1) = 11, a(n) = smallest prime obtained by inserting digits between every pair of digits of a(n-1).

A080440.name: a(1) = 13, a(n) = smallest prime obtained by inserting digits between every pair of digits of a(n-1).

A080441.name: a(1) = 17, a(n) = smallest prime obtained by inserting digits between every pair of digits of a(n-1).

A080442.name: a(1) = 19, a(n) = smallest prime obtained by inserting digits between every pair of digits of a(n-1).

A080445.name: a(1) = 1, a(n) = smallest (nontrivial) multiple of a(n-1) containing n digits, a(n) not equal to 10*a(n-1).

A080446.name: a(1) = 2, a(n) = smallest (nontrivial) multiple of a(n-1) containing n digits, a(n) not equal to 10*a(n-1).

A080447.name: a(1) = 3, a(n) = smallest (nontrivial) multiple of a(n-1) containing n digits, a(n) not equal to 10*a(n-1).

A080448.name: a(1) = 4, a(n) = smallest (nontrivial) multiple of a(n-1) containing n digits, a(n) not equal to 10*a(n-1). Also a(n) is not divisible by 10.

A080449.name: a(1) = 5, a(n) = smallest (nontrivial) multiple of a(n-1) containing n digits, a(n) not equal to 10*a(n-1). Also a(n) is not divisible by 10.

A080450.name: a(1) = 6, a(n) = smallest (nontrivial) multiple of a(n-1) containing n digits, a(n) not equal to 10*a(n-1). Also a(n) is not divisible by 10.

A080451.name: a(1) = 7, a(n) = smallest (nontrivial) multiple of a(n-1) containing n digits, a(n) not equal to 10*a(n-1).

A080452.name: a(1) = 8, a(n) = smallest (nontrivial) multiple of a(n-1) containing n digits, a(n) not equal to 10*a(n-1).

A080453.name: a(1) = 9, a(n) = smallest (nontrivial) multiple of a(n-1) containing n digits, a(n) not equal to 10*a(n-1).

E.g.f.: exp(x)*(1-x^2/2). - _Zerinvary Lajos_, Apr 05 2009, _R. J. Mathar_, Jun 11 2009
a(n) = - A214292(n,1) for n > 0. - _Reinhard Zumkeller_, Jul 12 2012

A080958.name: a(n) = n!*(2/1 - 3/2 + 4/3 - ... + s*(n+1)/n), where s = (-1)^(n+1).
formula: Conjecture: -(n+1)*a(n+1) + a(n) + n^2*(n+2)*a(n-1) = 0. - _R. J. Mathar_, Sep 27 2012, corrected for offset 1 by _Robert Israel_, Dec 26 2018
Conjecture verified, using the differential equation (x^3-x)*g''(x) + (5*x^2-1)*g'(x) + (3*x+1)*g(x) + 2 = 0 satisfied by the e.g.f. - _Robert Israel_, Dec 26 2018
a(n) = n!*(log(2) + (n mod 2) - (-1)^n*LerchPhi(-1, 1, n+1)). - _Peter Luschny_, Dec 26 2018

Expansion of psi(x) - x * psi(x^9) in powers of x^3 where psi() is a Ramanujan theta function. - _Michael Somos_, Sep 14 2007
Expansion of f(x, x^2) in powers of x where f() is Ramanujan's two-variable theta function.

G.f. is a period 1 Fourier series which satisfies f(-1 / (144 t)) = 2^(1/2) (t/i)^(1/2) g(t) where q = exp(2 Pi i t) and g() is the g.f. for A089810.

A080997.name: The positive integers arranged in nonincreasing order of centrality (the fraction of n represented by the average gcd of n and the other positive integers).
formula: Formula for centrality of n: A018804(n)/n^2, where A018804(n) is the sum of gcd (k, n) for 1 <= k <= n.
The centrality of a(n) is given by A080999(n)/(a(n))^2.

A080998.name: a(n) is n's rank among the positive integers in terms of centrality -the fraction of n represented by the average gcd of n and the positive integers, or A018804(n)/n^2 (cf. A080997).

A080999.name: Centrality of A080997(n) = a(n)/(A080997(n))^2.
formula: The multiplicative formula for the numerator in a positive integer's centrality fraction is: for prime p, a(p^e)= p^(e-1)*((p-1)e+p) (cf. A018804). Dividing by the square of the integer gives the integer's centrality, which is defined to be the average fraction of the integer that it shares with the other integers as a gcd; see A080997 for other interpretations. This sequence gives the unreduced centrality numerators for A080997(n), where A080997 is the sequence of positive integers in nonincreasing order of their centrality.

A081000.name: n is a member if and only if it ranks among top n positive integers in centrality (cf. A080997 for fuller description of this concept).
formula: The formula for the centrality of an integer is A018804(n)/n^2; see also A080997.
